198","1172":"1172","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1222":"1222","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1221":"1221","about 1202":"about 1202","about 1203":"about 1203","about 1200":"about 1200","Barton, Westmorland, England":"Barton, Westmorland, England","Craigie, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Craigie, Forfarshire, Scotland","Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Crawford, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Lamberton, Mordington, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Lamberton, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Avice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Aveza</i>, derived from a short form of one or more compound names containing the first element <i>av</i> (as in   Ava ;  the meaning is uncertain). The correspondence in form to the Latin word <i>avis</i> ‘bird’ is coincidental."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":38,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":47,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poi